        "results": [
          {
            "possibleIdentity": "Ludwig Redl is an Austrian-born sculptor and designer born in Vienna on September 12, 1942. He was notably active during the late 1960s and 1970s, living and working in California, London, and Rio de Janeiro. His artistic practice in the 1970s focused on sculptures made from unconventional materials such as fiberglass, twigs, and thread, often compared to the work of Eva Hesse. Redl held solo exhibitions at prestigious venues including the Galerie George Givaudaun in Paris (1969), Cirrus Gallery in Los Angeles (1975), and MoMA PS1 in New York (1977). During his time in California, he served as a professor of sculpture at the University of California, Santa Barbara (UCSB), where he was a mentor to students like the artist Jerry Cibilic. Later in his career, he transitioned into industrial design, becoming the head of design for Swarovski Crystal and a partner in the Austrian firm Gorgona Boehm Associates. His involvement with the Experiments in Art and Technology (E.A.T.) is supported by his participation in the avant-garde and experimental art circles of the 1970s, particularly his work at MoMA PS1 and his use of industrial materials and collaborative approaches characteristic of the E.A.T. era.",
